  <text>
    <body>
      <ab type="lido:objectWorkType">Photographic negative</ab>
      <ab type="lido:event" subtype="creation">
        <date>1924</date>
      <persName role="Press Photographer"><forename>Namık</forename><surname>Görgüç</surname><ref type="context" target="info:fedora/context:siba.pn.7d5d8ec5">Görgüç, Namık</ref></persName></ab>
      <ab type="lido:objectDescriptionSet">The well-known storyteller (meddah) Aşki Efendi is sitting on a wooden bench in a <ref target="http://gams.uni-graz.at/o:siba.glossar?mode=K2">kahvehane</ref>, looking at a newspaper he is holding with both hands. The text is in Ottoman script. Aşki Efendi is wearing a <ref target="http://gams.uni-graz.at/o:siba.glossar?mode=F4">fes</ref>, a wide collarless jacket made of the same material as his trousers, a collarless white shirt, and a handkerchief around his neck. He is sitting between two marble-topped tables with his elbow propped on the one to his right, which is covered with more newspapers.</ab>
      <ab type="lido:objectDescriptionSet" subtype="comment">The scene takes place in a <ref target="http://gams.uni-graz.at/o:siba.glossar?mode=K2">kahvehane</ref> in the Kadırga neighbourhood, Fatih. Ottoman script was in use in the Turkish Republic until 1928.</ab>
